style="color: light-dark(rgb(165, 29, 45), rgb(237, 237, 237));"><font style="font-size: 32px;">Domain Class Diagram</font></span></h1><p><font style="font-size: 16px;">The diagram shows domain classes interconnected by arrows which represent relationships among them. The system is going to be implemented over a webapp client-server architecture: each element of the system will be, some more some less, spread between client and server computation, while the final input/output interface will be a web browser displaying the webapp view.<br></font><font style="font-size: 16px;">Note that each class does not represent directly a code class, instead it represents an high level element which<br> forms the system. </font><font style="font-size: 16px;">For example CourseList and Course can be thought more to be mapped to webpages of the webapp, instead the the Chat element is more like a component of a webpage, while elements like AuthenticationManager and AuthorizationManager are more like functional/service components which in this case manage the security of access to the webpage functionalities and resources.<br>Each class element has some fields which represent a high level view of the properties associated to the component, in the implementation they may be formed of more properties and are going to be constituted of code variables and/or database fields.<br>The 1 or N over the arrows represent the multiplicity of the classes, for example is shown that CourseList, which represents the part of the webapp which shows a list of courses to the user who can enroll and open a specific course, can have N instances of Course, while each Course is associated just to one CourseList.<br>The white arrow represents specialization of a more abstract element, for example a User can be a Student or a Teacher and each one respectively has some specific fields and permissions (e.g. only teachers can use the functionalities to edit their own courses).</font></p>" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" vertex="1" parent="1"> <mxGeometry x="80" y="480" width="920" height="480" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> </root> </mxGraphModel> </diagram> </mxfile>

p.font: The diagram shows domain classes interconnected by arrows which represent relationships among them. The system is going to be implemented over a webapp client-server architecture: each element of the system will be, some more some less, spread between client and server computation, while the final input/output interface will be a web browser displaying the webapp view.

Note that each class does not represent directly a code class, instead it represents an high level element which
forms the system.

For example CourseList and Course can be thought more to be mapped to webpages of the webapp, instead the the Chat element is more like a component of a webpage, while elements like AuthenticationManager and AuthorizationManager are more like functional/service components which in this case manage the security of access to the webpage functionalities and resources.
Each class element has some fields which represent a high level view of the properties associated to the component, in the implementation they may be formed of more properties and are going to be constituted of code variables and/or database fields.
The 1 or N over the arrows represent the multiplicity of the classes, for example is shown that CourseList, which represents the part of the webapp which shows a list of courses to the user who can enroll and open a specific course, can have N instances of Course, while each Course is associated just to one CourseList.
The white arrow represents specialization of a more abstract element, for example a User can be a Student or a Teacher and each one respectively has some specific fields and permissions (e.g. only teachers can use the functionalities to edit their own courses).
